10 NEW SECTION. Section 1. Nutrient pollutant loading offsets AND TRADING CREDITS. (1) A point
11 source discharger permitted UNDER A PERMIT ISSUED pursuant to this part 75-5-401, A POINT SOURCE DISCHARGER
12 TO STATE SURFACE WATERS may receive a nutrient pollutant loading offset OFFSETS OR TRADING CREDITS to
13 achieve SATISFY PERMITTING REQUIREMENTS, INCLUDING NUTRIENT EFFLUENT LIMITATIONS ESTABLISHED PURSUANT
14 TO THIS PART AND NUTRIENT EFFLUENT LIMITATIONS DERIVED FROM waste load allocations set by: ESTABLISHED
15 PURSUANT TO 75-5-703.
16 (a) a total maximum daily load requirement established pursuant to 75-5-703; or
17 (b) a numeric nutrient effluent limitation established pursuant to this part.
18 (2) If the actions in subsections (1)(a) and (1)(b) decrease the nutrient loading in a watershed, the
19 department may:
20 (a) issue or modify a discharge permit authorized pursuant to this part to allow discharges of
21 nutrients to a receiving water body ; or
22 (b) authorize a reduction in nutrient loading from point and nonpoint pollution sources within the
23 same 12-digit hydrologic unit code subbasin as designated by the United States geological survey.
24 (2) NUTRIENT LOADING OFFSETS AND TRADING CREDITS MAY BE AUTHORIZED FOR INCREASES IN OR
25 CONTINUATION OF NUTRIENT DISCHARGES WHEN A NET DECREASE IN NUTRIENT LOADING WITHIN THE UNITED STATES
26 GEOLOGICAL SURVEY-DESIGNATED 12-DIGIT HYDROLOGIC UNIT CODE SUBBASIN, OR IMMEDIATELY ADJACENT 12-DIGIT
27 HYDROLOGIC UNIT CODE SUBBASIN WHEN THE PROJECT IS IN CLOSE PROXIMITY TO THE ADJACENT 12-DIGIT HYDROLOGIC
28 UNIT CODE SUBBASIN, IS ACHIEVED THROUGH REDUCTIONS FROM OTHER POINT SOURCES OR NONPOINT SOURCES
